To: Museum Security Network Mailinglist <msn-list@te.verweg.com>
Message-ID: <46552498.8060305@bruggemansolutions.com>
Content-Type: text/plain; charset=UTF-8; format=flowed

Burglars make off with artwork
By SALVADOR HERNANDEZ
The Orange County Register
Monday, May 21, 2007

LAGUNA BEACH ? A burglary has left police looking into how thieves walked away with about $750,000 worth of paintings from a local artist's home and wondering how the perpetrators plan to get rid of the easily identifiable loot.

In the unusual burglary, police say at least one burglar stole two bicycles and about 250 framed oil paintings by local artist John Cosby, a plein-air painter whose work has been featured in galleries in Laguna Beach and across the nation.

"It was like a decorator robbed my house," he said.

Only three of Cosby's paintings, which were unframed, were left behind.

"Either they were incredibly picky, or everyone is an art critic now," he said. "It almost made me insecure of the painting."

Cosby was away in South Carolina between April 23 and 29, when police believe the burglary occurred. He had just moved in to his new home in March and a side door to the two-car garage where the paintings were being temporarily stored was left unsecured.

Art thefts are not a rare occurrence in Laguna Beach, said Detective Debbie Kelso. The city has an active artistic community and several art galleries line city streets, but a theft of this magnitude is unheard of, she said.

Police have contacted other police agencies and art galleries to be on the lookout.

The paintings should be easily identifiable, Kelso said. Each one was signed by Cosby twice and contained a serial number.

Contact the writer: shernandez@ocregister.com or 949-454-7361

http://www.ocregister.com/





